subSubSection.paragraph:
Skeleton
(
Figs 3a–d
): Between the papillae, there is a distinct cortex of up to 
1.5 mm
in thickness (
Figs 3a–b
), strengthened by a 
200–300 µm
thick palisade of small tylostyles (
Fig. 3b
), underneath of which there are subdermal lacunae amid tissues lacking choanocytes, overlying a mass of intercrossing single large tylostyles, here and there united in bundles making an irregular subectosomal reticulation. In the choanosome the skeleton is made of large tylostyles arranged in an irregular reticulation of vague bundles with many loose single spicules. The skeleton of the papillae (
Figs 3c–d
) is more compressed, with subdermal reticulation largely absent, although the intercrossing spicule layer is clearly present (
Fig. 3d
).
